#compdef marked
# ============================================================================
# marked - canonical Node markdown parser +
#           reference CLI from the markedjs
#           organization
#           (TypeScript/Node, MIT)
#
# Author : Christopher Jeffrey + Tony Brix +
#           markedjs organization
# Upstream: https://github.com/markedjs/marked
# npm pkg : marked
#
# `marked` is the canonical Node.js markdown
# parser - a low-level CommonMark + GitHub
# Flavored Markdown (GFM) compiler with a
# pluggable extension system. The shipped CLI
# (`marked` binary) is the reference end-user
# interface to the library's API + powers
# countless downstream tools.
#
# Distinguishing features vs alternatives:
#   - **Canonical Node markdown parser**
#     (the markedjs/marked package is the
#     reference Node markdown
#     implementation; ~17M weekly npm
#     downloads)
#   - **CommonMark + GFM** (GitHub Flavored
#     Markdown extensions native: tables +
#     strikethrough + tasklists + autolinks
#     + footnotes)
#   - **Pluggable extension system** (use()
#     for custom renderers + tokenizers +
#     hooks)
#   - **Token output mode** (--tokens
#     produces the token AST as JSON;
#     useful for downstream processing
#     pipelines)
#   - **Config file support** (--config
#     loads marked configuration from JSON
#     + ESM modules; enables option
#     management as code)
#   - **Stdin pipeline mode** (no input file
#     = read from stdin; suitable for
#     shell pipelines)
#   - **Browser-compatible** (same library
#     runs in browsers via the ESM bundle)
#
# Use cases:
#   - Convert markdown files to HTML at the
#     command line (replacement for pandoc
#     in markdown-only workflows)
#   - Server-side rendering of user-
#     submitted markdown content (forums +
#     comment systems + chat apps)
#   - Static site generators that prefer
#     marked over markdown-it (smaller
#     bundle; simpler API)
#   - CI pipelines that need markdown ->
#     HTML conversion (release notes +
#     changelog rendering + documentation
#     compilation)
#   - Token output for syntax tree analysis
#     (--tokens mode produces JSON AST
#     suitable for jq-based analysis)
#
# Usage:
#   marked [options] [files...]
#   echo "# hello" | marked      # stdin
#
# Input options:
#   -i, --input <file>             - input
#                                     markdown
#                                     file
#   -s, --string <string>          - inline
#                                     markdown
#                                     string
#                                     (instead
#                                     of file)
#   [files...]                     - input
#                                     markdown
#                                     files
#                                     (positional)
#
# Output options:
#   -o, --output <file>            - output
#                                     file
#                                     (default
#                                     stdout)
#   -n, --no-clobber               - do not
#                                     overwrite
#                                     output
#                                     file if
#                                     it
#                                     exists
#   -t, --tokens                   - emit
#                                     JSON
#                                     token
#                                     AST
#                                     instead
#                                     of HTML
#                                     (the
#                                     intermediate
#                                     marked
#                                     representation
#                                     - useful
#                                     for
#                                     downstream
#                                     analysis)
#
# Config:
#   -c, --config <file>            - load
#                                     marked
#                                     configuration
#                                     from
#                                     file
#                                     (JSON or
#                                     ESM
#                                     module
#                                     exporting
#                                     options
#                                     or a
#                                     function
#                                     that
#                                     calls
#                                     marked
#                                     .use())
#
# Marked option flags (any marked.defaults
# key can be passed as --<key> = <value> or
# --<key> for booleans or --no-<key> to
# disable):
#       --gfm                      - enable
#                                     GitHub
#                                     Flavored
#                                     Markdown
#                                     (default
#                                     true)
#       --no-gfm                   - disable
#                                     GFM
#       --breaks                   - convert
#                                     line
#                                     breaks
#                                     to <br>
#                                     (default
#                                     false)
#       --no-breaks                - disable
#                                     line
#                                     break
#                                     conversion
#       --pedantic                 - strictly
#                                     follow
#                                     the
#                                     original
#                                     markdown
#                                     .pl
#                                     (default
#                                     false)
#       --no-pedantic              - disable
#                                     pedantic
#                                     mode
#       --silent                   - silence
#                                     error
#                                     output
#                                     (default
#                                     false)
#
# Standard:
#   -h, --help                     - show
#                                     manual
#                                     page
#                                     (man
#                                     marked
#                                     if
#                                     available)
#   -v, --version                  - show
#                                     version
#
# Example invocations:
#   # Convert a markdown file to HTML
#   marked -i README.md -o README.html
#
#   # Convert via stdin pipeline
#   cat README.md | marked > README.html
#
#   # Inline string conversion
#   marked -s '# Hello, **world**!'
#
#   # Emit JSON token AST instead of HTML
#   marked -i README.md -t
#
#   # Disable GFM + breaks + use pedantic
#   # mode (closer to original markdown.pl)
#   marked --no-gfm --no-breaks --pedantic \
#     -i README.md
#
#   # Multiple input files concatenated
#   marked chapter1.md chapter2.md chapter3.md \
#     -o book.html
#
#   # Use a config file
#   marked -c marked.config.mjs -i README.md \
#     -o README.html
#
#   # Stdin + write to output file with
#   # no-clobber protection
#   echo "# Hello" | marked -o out.html -n
#
# Configuration file (marked.config.mjs):
#   ```javascript
#   import { gfmHeadingId } from
#     'marked-gfm-heading-id';
#   import { markedHighlight } from
#     'marked-highlight';
#
#   export default {
#     // marked options
#     breaks: true,
#     gfm: true,
#     pedantic: false,
#     // extensions
#     extensions: [
#       gfmHeadingId({ prefix: 'my-' })
#     ],
#     // or a function that calls marked.use()
#     // function(marked) {
#     //   marked.use(gfmHeadingId());
#     //   marked.use(markedHighlight({ ... }));
#     // }
#   };
#   ```
#
# Marked extensions ecosystem (some popular
# packages):
#   marked-gfm-heading-id          - GFM-
#                                     compliant
#                                     heading
#                                     id
#                                     generation
#   marked-highlight               - syntax
#                                     highlighting
#                                     (paired
#                                     with
#                                     highlight
#                                     .js or
#                                     shiki)
#   marked-mangle                  - email
#                                     address
#                                     mangling
#                                     for spam
#                                     protection
#   marked-base-url                - rewrite
#                                     relative
#                                     URLs to
#                                     absolute
#   marked-katex-extension         - inline +
#                                     display
#                                     math via
#                                     KaTeX
#   marked-footnote                - GFM
#                                     footnote
#                                     syntax
#   marked-smartypants             - smart
#                                     punctuation
#                                     (curly
#                                     quotes +
#                                     em-dashes
#                                     + ...)
#   marked-extended-tables         - extended
#                                     table
#                                     syntax
#   marked-terminal                - render
#                                     markdown
#                                     to ANSI
#                                     for
#                                     terminal
#                                     display
#                                     (used by
#                                     dozens
#                                     of CLI
#                                     tools
#                                     including
#                                     terminalGPT
#                                     + Firebase
#                                     CLI +
#                                     task-
#                                     master
#                                     + diginext)
#
# The marked lane IS the canonical Node
# markdown parser - this CLI is the
# reference end-user interface to the
# library by the markedjs organization
# (github.com/markedjs/marked).
#
# markedjs/marked is the de-facto canonical
# Node markdown parser:
#   - **CommonMark v0.30 compatibility**
#     (passes the CommonMark spec
#     compliance suite with documented
#     edge cases)
#   - **Pure JavaScript implementation**
#     (no native bindings; runs in Node +
#     browsers + Deno + Bun + Cloudflare
#     Workers)
#   - **GFM extensions** (tables +
#     strikethrough + tasklists +
#     autolinks + footnotes)
#   - **Pluggable architecture** (use()
#     for extensions; custom tokenizers +
#     renderers + hooks)
#   - **TypeScript types included** (the
#     marked package ships with @types
#     declarations)
#   - **~17,000,000 weekly npm downloads**
#     (one of the highest-volume Node
#     libraries)
#   - 35,000+ stars on github.com/markedjs/
#     marked
#
# markedjs/marked's distinguishing position
# vs Node markdown alternatives:
#   - markedjs/marked (Jeffrey + Brix +
#     org): canonical; ~17M weekly
#     downloads; THIS AXIS
#   - markdown-it (Vitaly Puzrin /
#     nodeca): alternative canonical; ~14M
#     weekly npm downloads; pluggable
#     architecture; used by markdownlint
#     + many Vue/React docs sites
#   - commonmark.js (jgm/commonmark.js;
#     John MacFarlane): the CommonMark
#     reference implementation in JS; by
#     the CommonMark spec author; not as
#     widely adopted as marked or
#     markdown-it
#   - remark (unifiedjs/remark): full
#     markdown AST processor; broader
#     scope; powers MDX + many
#     transformation pipelines
#   - micromark (unifiedjs/micromark):
#     low-level CommonMark parser; powers
#     remark internally
#
# Christopher Jeffrey is the original author
# of marked (started 2011 as a markdown.pl
# port). Tony Brix is the long-time
# maintainer + primary release manager.
# The markedjs organization (formerly
# chjj/marked under Jeffrey's username)
# now hosts the project + maintains it
# collaboratively.
#
# Christopher Jeffrey's broader Node
# ecosystem footprint:
#   - markedjs/marked (canonical Node
#     markdown parser; THIS AXIS)
#   - chjj/blessed (canonical Node curses
#     library; ~5,200 stars; the basis of
#     many Node TUI applications)
#   - chjj/hsk (Handshake protocol
